ic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Meschin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Meacham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Meacham","meanings":["English: variant of   Machen  . It may occasionally also be a variant of <b>Measham</b>, a habitational name from Measham in Leicestershire. The place takes its name from the river Mease (from Old English <i>mēos</i> ‘marsh, bog’) + Old English <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’."]}]},{"name":"Ier","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and Norwegian vernacular form of   Peter ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peter","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Guigues Meschin Ier de Châteauneuf-Randon was born about 1145, in Châteauneuf-de-Randon, Lozère, Occitanie, France. He married Guillemette de Ceyssac on 22 February 1175, in Rodez, Aveyron, Occitanie, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 1229, in his hometown."},"et":{"environ 1145–après 1229":"umbes 1145–pärast 1229"